post_text:
St. John Parish Update

Tropical Storm Sally is projected to make landfall sometime Tuesday morning as a possible Category 1 Hurricane. St. John Parish is currently under Hurricane, Storm Surge and Flash Flood Watches. Periods of heavy rainfall, strong winds and coastal flooding remain the greatest threats through Thursday.

Parish President Hotard would like to encourage residents to complete all hurricane preparations before the weekend ends as conditions could start to deteriorate as early as Monday afternoon. Residents can assist with potential heavy rainfall and winds by clearing and unclogging drains and catch basins around homes and securing garbage cans and other loose debris.

Parish crews are out working, checking drainage and utilities systems and will be throughout the remainder of the event. Please continue to follow Parish information outlets for updates and text SJPWEATHER to 888-777 for the latest on Tropical Storm Sally.

post_text:
Today, Parish President Hotard and Capital Projects crews delivered supplies that were donated by St. John residents and employees to the United Way in Lake Charles. Upon delivery, President Hotard was greeted by Lake Charles Mayor Nic Hunter who updated President Hotard on recovery efforts and expressed his sincere gratitude for the donations.

‚ÄúI can‚Äôt thank St. John enough for doing this,‚Äù said Mayor Hunter. ‚ÄúIt means the world to me and this entire area. God bless all of you.‚Äù

President Hotard added ‚ÄúWitnessing the devastation in Lake Charles today was truly heartbreaking. We understand wholeheartedly what these residents are going through because we have been there. I want to thank all of the residents and businesses who contributed last week during the donation drive. It is truly appreciated and will be given to those who need it most.‚Äù

post_text:
St. John Parish Supports Displaced Hurricane Laura Residents Staying in St. John Parish

Parish President Hotard and staff visited hotels over the weekend to welcome and offer support to residents displaced by Hurricane Laura.

In addition to bringing supplies and meeting with CARC representatives, President Hotard and team shared meals with those staying in St. John Parish. Additional efforts to support these residents are underway.

"We wholeheartedly empathize with those recovering from Hurricane Laura and will do everything we can to assist them while they are staying in our community," said Parish President Hotard. "Our neighbors to the West were very generous to us after Hurricane Isaac and this represents another opportunity to return the favor to people in need."

President Hotard also teamed up with the St. John United Way to collect donations for hard hit areas. Supplies and non-perishable food items can be donated through Sept. 4 from 8:30 a.m. to 6:00 p.m. at the St. John Community Center in LaPlace. To make a monetary donation, please visit www.stjohnunitedway.org.

**Hurricane Laura Donation Drive**

Beginning today through Friday, supplies for residents impacted by Hurricane Laura can be dropped off from 8:30 a.m. ‚Äì 6:00 p.m.at the St. John Community Center, 2900 Hwy 51 in LaPlace.

The following is a list of items that the Parish is collecting:
Water
Toilet paper
Hand sanitizer
Toothbrushes/toothpaste
Soap
Shampoo
Deodorant
Feminine products
Depends (men/women)
Baby food, formula, bottles, diapers, wipes
Cleaning & sanitizing products
Masks
Package undergarments & socks (No other clothing will be expected per FEMA guidelines)
Towels
Non-perishable foods (Gatorade, pop tarts, granola bars)

Thank you for your generosity. #StJohnStrong
text:
**Hurricane Laura Donation Drive**

Beginning today through Friday, supplies for residents impacted by Hurricane Laura can be dropped off from 8:30 a.m. ‚Äì 6:00 p.m.at the St. John Community Center, 2900 Hwy 51 in LaPlace.

The following is a list of items that the Parish is collecting:
Water
Toilet paper
Hand sanitizer
Toothbrushes/toothpaste
Soap
Shampoo
Deodorant
Feminine products
Depends (men/women)
Baby food, formula, bottles, diapers, wipes
Cleaning & sanitizing products
Masks
Package undergarments & socks (No other clothing will be expected per FEMA guidelines)
Towels
Non-perishable foods (Gatorade, pop tarts, granola bars)

Thank you for your generosity. #StJohnStrong

post_text:
Today marks the 8th Anniversary of Hurricane Isaac. On August 29, 2012, Hurricane Isaac devastated more than 7,000 homes and businesses in St. John Parish and drastically changed the lives of so many.

Join Parish President Hotard, Council and staff in remembering the resiliency, strength and kindness reflected within the community in one of our darkest hours.

As we commemorate the 8th anniversary of Hurricane Isaac, more than ever we must hold tight to the notion that as long as we work together and stay strong, there is always a brighter tomorrow. May we also take a moment to pray for our neighbors to the west as they recover from Hurricane Laura. #StJohnStrong

President Hotard to Reopen Sandbag Sites Tuesday, August 25, 2020

Residents are asked to use extreme caution when going out to the sandbag sites as Tropical Storm Laura may begin to threaten the area.

President Hotard Issues Voluntary Evacuation for low-lying areas North of I-10 & Pleasure Bend

Parish President Jaclyn Hotard issues a voluntary evacuation for Pleasure Bend and areas North of I-10 in LaPlace, including Frenier, Peavine and Manchac in advance of Tropical Storm Marco and Tropical Storm Laura. The order goes into effect at 1:00 p.m. central, Sunday, August 23, 2020.

Residents are asked to bring vehicles, boats or campers to higher ground as Tropical Storm Marco and Tropical Storm Laura could bring in storm surges and heavy rainfall from Monday- Thursday.

‚ÄúWe are taking all necessary precautions in advance of the unpredictable situation of two Hurricanes possibly impacting St. John Parish within days of each other,‚Äù said Parish President Jaclyn Hotard. ‚ÄúCrews have been working all weekend installing temporary generators, clearing catch basins and facilitating sandbag sites. It is critical that residents finalize all hurricane preparations today as conditions are expected to worsen early Monday.‚Äù

St. John Parish Mourns the Loss of Former Chief Deputy Assessor Bruno Burrell

Today, St. John Parish is mourning the loss of former Chief Deputy Assessor Bruno Burrell, who was called home to the Lord yesterday evening. Bruno was a true public servant who spent the majority of his life working tirelessly for the best interests of our community. His lively spirit touched the lives of many in St. John Parish and beyond and he will be sorely missed. Please join Parish President Jaclyn Hotard, Parish Council and staff in praying for his wife, children, family, friends, and his lifelong dear friend Former Assessor Whitney Joseph during this difficult time.

St. John Parish Declares Emergency Ahead of Possible Tropical Impact

Parish President Hotard signed an Emergency Declaration in advance of Tropical Storm Marco and Tropical Storm Laura to allow parish officials to take precautionary measures and ensure the safety of St. John Parish Residents.

Although intensity and forecast for both systems remain uncertain, heavy rainfall, strong winds and elevated tides could possibly impact Louisiana early next week. Residents are asked to assist in removing loose debris and trash in catch basins at home in advance of inclement weather.

Public Works crews are out checking pump stations and blowing out drainage outlets. The Utilities Department is also monitoring all lift stations and generators for the water and wastewater systems.

Please visit sjbparish.com or follow the Parish on the Government Access Channel, Facebook, Twitter and Instagram for updates.

shared_text:
NOAA NWS National Hurricane Center
August 20 at 6:12 PM ¬∑

The National Hurricane Center is issuing advisories on Tropical Depression Thirteen, located several hundred miles east of the northern Leeward Islands - www.nhc.noaa.gov/#Thirteen - and on newly formed Tropical Depression Fourteen, located a couple of hundred miles east of the Honduras/Nicaragua border www.nhc.noaa.gov/Fourteen.

Elsewhere over the Alantic basin on this Thursday afternoon, a tropical wave is nearing the western Africa coast, producing disorganized showers and thunderstorms within a few hundred miles of the coastline. This wave is expected to move over the far eastern tropical Atlantic on Friday, and some slow development is possible through the weekend while it moves west-northwestward at 15 to 20 mph across the eastern tropical Atlantic. It has a low (20 percent) chance of formation during the next 48 hours and a medium (40 percent) chance during the next five days. www.hurricanes.gov

post_text:
The National Hurricane Center is now monitoring three tropical waves - here is the latest:

The first one is slowly getting more organized and has a high 80% chance for development this weekend into next week. It could be in the southern Gulf of Mexico by early next week and may be a threat to Texas.

The second one is in the Atlantic, a 1000 miles east of the Caribbean. It has become better organized and it has a high 90% chance for development. It has the potential to reach the Gulf of Mexico next week and could be a threat to anyone on the northern Gulf coast.

The third one is getting ready to move off the coast of Africa and travel west across the Atlantic. It has a low 30% chance for development. It is much too early to know if this poses a threat to the Gulf of Mexico.

Please stay weather aware and #Ready. #StJohnStrong

The first tropical wave, nearing the Windward Islands, has a medium 50% chance of becoming a tropical depression late this week or weekend in the Caribbean Sea. This system could be in the Gulf of Mexico by early next week.

The second tropical wave, far out in the Atlantic, has a high 70% chance of becoming a tropical system later this week as it approaches the Caribbean Sea.

Please stay tuned to updates and ensure you and your family have a game plan if needed. Remember we are approaching the peak of hurricane season. #StJohnStrong #Hurricane #Preparedness #GetaGamePlan

President Hotard & Crews Respond to Severe Weather Event in Mt. Airy

Parish President Hotard and Parish crews are in Mt. Airy working to pick up tree limbs and clear roadways of vegetative debris as a result of strong, straight-line winds that passed through the area earlier this afternoon. The severe weather also downed numerous power lines resulting in an extended power outage.

Residents and motorists in the Mt. Airy area should use caution on roadways and be on the lookout for crews and equipment. #StJohnStrong #staysafe #Entergy #riverparishes

post_text:
Showers and thunderstorms are possible across the area through Tuesday. These will have the capability to produce heavy rainfall.

Possible Impacts:
‚Ä¢ An additional 1.5 to 4 inches of rainfall is currently forecast over the next 2 days. Locally higher amounts are expected.

We are also monitoring a tropical wave in the Atlantic that has a high chance of developing into a depression or storm in the next 2 to 5 days. It is too soon to say whether this system will have an impact on the gulf coast.

Please stay #WeatherReady this week. Remember, we are still in hurricane season and now is a good time to review your plans.

Update on the Tropics: The National Hurricane Center has increased the chance for tropical development to 50 percent for a tropical wave approaching the central Gulf of Mexico. This system could become a tropical depression this week as it heads towards Texas.

The primary weather hazards for our Parish from this system will be increased rain chances and elevated tides. We also remain under a Marginal Risk for excessive rainfall on Thursday, which has now been extended into Friday.

Elsewhere, tropical depression seven out in the Atlantic Ocean will likely become Tropical Storm Gonzalo today. This system poses no threat to the Gulf this week, but we will need to monitor it next week. #StJohnStrong #StayWeatherReady

Governor Extends Phase Two Until August 7, 2020

Today, Tuesday, July 21, 2020 Governor John Bel Edwards announced that he is extending Phase Two of Reopening in Louisiana for an additional two weeks until August 7, 2020.

As a reminder, additional restrictions in Phase Two include:
-A mask mandate for ages eight and older unless the individual meets an exemption exception as outlined in the full order.
-All Bars with and without LDH food permits are closed indoors. Bars can offer curbside pickup.
-Indoor gatherings are limited to 50 people.

The Governor‚Äôs Office will post the updated proclamation later this week via gov.louisiana.gov. Businesses can send reopening questions to stjohnstrong@stjohn-la.gov or register at opensafely.gov.

post_text:
Here is an update on the Tropics:

The National Hurricane Center is monitoring a weak low pressure system in the northwestern Gulf of Mexico. It is expected to move inland over Texas tonight or Tuesday. It only has a low 10 percent chance of developing.

A tropical wave in the Bahamas is expected to reach the eastern Gulf of Mexico on Tuesday, and be in the northwestern Gulf by Thursday. There is a low 20 percent chance of developing.

Further out in the Atlantic there is a tropical wave that has a low 20 percent chance for development, but by this weekend it will be in a less favorable environment.

Higher rain chances and elevated tides are expected this week for our Parish. Stay weather ready this week.

Governor John Bel Edwards Issues Statewide Mask Mandate and Additional COVID-19 Restrictions Effective Monday, July 13, 2020

Today, Governor John Bel Edwards announced additional Coronavirus restrictions for Louisiana effective Monday, July 13, 2020 until Friday, July 24, 2020 including:

-A Statewide mask mandate for all individuals ages eight and older unless the individual meets an exemption exception as outlined in the full order: https://gov.louisiana.gov/index.cfm/newsroom/detail/2591
-All Bars with and without LDH food permits will close indoors. Bars can offer curbside pickup.
-Indoor gatherings are limited to 50 people.

Phase Two Reopening guidance should continue to be followed. For specific guidance and additional information, please visit gov.louisiana.gov. Businesses can send questions to stjohnstrong@stjohn-la.gov or register at opensafely.gov.

July 2 at 7:31 PM ¬∑

St. John Parish Government Complex Re-Opening

The St. John Parish Government Complex will re-open to the public effective Monday, July 6, 2020 at 8 a.m. The following will be in place:

-- All persons entering the Government Complex will be required to have their temperature taken by Ochsner Health staff.
-- All persons entering the Government Complex will be required to wear a facial mask or covering.

To help minimize the spread of the coronavirus, the Parish encourages the public to use electronic or other non-contact means of conducting Parish business whenever possible, such as utilizing the Dropbox at the entrance the Government Complex and online services for water bill payments and scheduling an appointment with the appropriate department.

All residents and businesses are encouraged to continue to follow the Phase Two reopening guidance and Coronavirus precautions from the Governor's Office, the Louisiana Department of Health, the State Fire Marshal's Office and the CDC.

*18 years or older

*Testing is free.

post_text:
St. John Parish Cristobal Update

Tropical Storm Cristobal is forecast to make landfall along the Louisiana Coast soon. St. John Parish is currently under a Tropical Storm Warning and Flash Flood Watch. Heavy rainfall of 4 to 8 inches through Tuesday and storm surge remain the greatest threats.

Parish President Hotard would like to remind residents that now is the time to stay home and monitor weather conditions. "All preparations should be complete, and we are asking residents to stay off roadways during inclement weather and not let your guard down as severe conditions are still possible through the night."

To report power outages, please call 1-8009OUTAGE . Please also remember to stay away from downed power lines for safety.

Here is the 6/6/20 4:00 p.m. Advisory. Conditions will start to deteriorate overnight and heavy rainfall and strong wind will be moving in.

Now is the time to finalize preparations and hunker down. The timeframe for impacts is as early as tonight through the day tomorrow. As we move into, Monday, the wind, surge, and severe threat should improve as the storm moves north. Please do not get on roadways if you don't have to during the storm and never drive down flooded streets.

post_text:
Tropical Storm Watch - The National Hurricane Center has issued a Tropical Storm Watch for portions of the Louisiana and the northern Gulf of Mexico Coast including St. John the Baptist Parish. Tropical storm conditions are possible within the Tropical Storm Watch area of the northern Gulf coast beginning early Sunday.

Although the track remains uncertain, torrential downpours and rainfall amounts of 4 to 10 inches with locally higher amounts are possible. Other threats include higher than normal tides, coastal flooding and strong tropical storm force winds. #preparenow #cristobal
